Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
A few hours ago, a magnitude 7.3 earthquake struck off the Alaska Peninsula, just south of Sand Point. Local residents and summer visitors alike were able to evacuate thanks to federal tsunami advisories relayed through local public broadcasting stations.

That‚Äôs the real world. But here in the U.S. Senate, we are currently debating a rescissions package that would severely cut funding for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, drastically affecting Alaska‚Äôs 27 public media stations and many more across the nation. 

Some colleagues claim they are targeting ‚Äúradical leftist organizations‚Äù with these cuts, but in Alaska, these are simply organizations dedicated to their communities. Their response to today‚Äôs earthquake is a perfect example of the incredible public service these stations provide. They deliver local news, weather updates, and, yes, emergency alerts that save human lives. 

I want to thank KMXT in Kodiak, KUCB in Unalaska, and KSDP in Sand Point for giving Alaskans real-time updates and keeping us safe. 

The tsunami warnings are now thankfully canceled, but the warning to the U.S. Senate remains in effect. Today of all days, we should vote down these misguided cuts to public broadcasting.

Name: Sewell, Terri A.
text:
It is hard to believe that five years have passed since we lost John. He would have a lot to say about what‚Äôs going on these days. The attacks on our democracy. The whitewashing of our history. The efforts to make it harder for Americans to vote.

Old battles have indeed become new again, but if there is one thing that John taught us, it‚Äôs that we must press on!

When I am at my most distraught, I think about John's words as he crossed the Edmund Pettus Bridge for the last time before his passing. His body was frail and riddled with cancer but his mind was sharp and his charge to us was clear.

‚ÄúNever give up. Never give in. Keep the faith, and keep your eyes on the prize.‚Äù

My friends, we are living through troubling times. We can be tired. We can be frustrated. We can be downright mad. But what we cannot do is give up.

Just imagine where we would be if John Lewis and those Foot Soldiers had given up on Bloody Sunday. They were beaten, bruised, gassed, and whipped. They had every reason to throw up their hands and surrender!

But they didn't. They got back up and tried again. They marched on until victory was won.

Now more than ever, we need to take a page from their playbook.

As we navigate this dark chapter of our history, let‚Äôs keep the faith, and let‚Äôs continue to get into some Good Trouble.

For John, and the nation he so loved. üíï

Name: Salazar, Maria Elvira
text:
This is incorrect.

This is a provision from the Dream Act included in the bill. No criminals or gang members are eligible. Period. 

Here‚Äôs how it works ‚Äî when a Dreamer would apply to adjust status, there is an investigation - including a criminal background check, check for gang affiliation, and more. 

During that investigation, the federal and state gang database network can absolutely be a factor in determining gang membership, but the presence on a list alone does not disqualify them immediately.

There must be another factor to prove gang membership - which could be a criminal charge (not just conviction), tattoos, gang dress, evidence from law enforcement investigations, social media, witness testimony, prison records, etc. 

Also, the burden is on the Dreamer to prove they qualify for adjusted status - so if they are on a database (or not on a database, but there is other proof of gang membership), they have to prove that is incorrect. 

This is because the gang databases have proven inaccurate in federal courts. 

Just like many who have found themselves incorrectly flagged on a database - NICS (gun purchases), No Fly list, etc - when they shouldn‚Äôt be. 

So when it comes to gang membership, it means ‚Äî Gang database + another factor. 

That‚Äôs it - simple. Not a smoking gun.

Name: Loudermilk, Barry
text:
MYTH: NPR/PBS provide unbiased, quality news coverage.

FACT: While the broadcasters are statutorily required to ensure ‚Äústrict adherence to objectivity and balance in all programs or series of programs of a controversial nature‚Äù (47 U.S.C. ¬ß 396(g)(1)(D)), they have never complied with that legal obligation. Instead, they have flouted the law, going out of their way to produce news media that is favorable to left-leaning politicians and institutions. For this reason alone, NPR and PBS should be deprived of federal funding.

According to an MRC report, recent examples include:
PBS:
1. 162 references to ‚Äúfar right‚Äù vs only 6 references to ‚Äúfar left‚Äù
2. 6 times as many liberal political guests as conservative guests
3. 88% positive coverage of the DNC vs 72% negative coverage of the RNC

NPR:
1. Banned coverage of the Hunter Biden laptop story, claiming it was a ‚Äúmere distraction‚Äù

Name: Loudermilk, Barry
text:

It is easier than ever before for Americans to find news via the internet, and to come to their own conclusions about the news they‚Äôre reading, rather than having that information dictated to them by biased NPR reporters.

Name: Durbin, Richard J.
text:
Today‚Äôs Committee executive business meeting included 10 nominees‚Äîamong them Emil Bove, nominated for a lifetime appointment on the federal bench.

Mr. Bove belongs nowhere near the federal bench.

He led the Administration‚Äôs effort to strike a corrupt bargain with New York City Mayor Eric Adams and has been trailed by a history of complaints‚Äîlong predating his affiliation with President Trump‚Äîabout his temperament, poor judgment, and lack of candor before the court.

Additionally, Erez Reuveni, a career Justice Department attorney who defended the first Trump Administration‚Äôs immigration policies, filed a whistleblower complaint with my office regarding Mr. Bove.

That complaint recounted that Mr. Bove suggested DOJ might need to say "f--- you" to federal courts that issued orders that the Administration opposed.

I asked Mr. Reuveni whether he could substantiate his claims, and in response, he provided text messages, email exchanges, and other documents corroborating his allegations.

Given Mr. Reuveni‚Äôs credible allegations against Mr. Bove, which, if true, clearly disqualify him for a lifetime appointment to the federal bench, I called for the Committee to hear from Mr. Reuveni, under oath, before we voted on Mr. Bove‚Äôs nomination.

But Chairman Grassley denied that request.

And today, he cut off debate time on Mr. Bove‚Äôs nomination before turning to his vote, as well as nine other nominations, including Ms. Pirro‚Äôs.

Chairman Grassley claimed that he was following Committee precedent. This is simply untrue.

When I was Chair, I only limited debate when Republicans invoked Senate rules to shut down Committee meetings, and after Committee members were given ample opportunities to voice their concerns about nominees on the agenda.

Today, Chairman Grassley blocked Democratic members from discussing the controversial records of nominees like Emil Bove and Jeanine Pirro, shut down debate, and forced votes for no apparent reason.

My question is this: what are my Senate Republican colleagues trying to hide?

text:
Today I took a moment to pray and reflect in the Congressional Prayer Room. It‚Äôs a quiet space near the Capitol rotunda, set aside in 1955 for Members of Congress to seek spiritual guidance.

The stained glass window shows George Washington in prayer, surrounded by the powerful words from Lincoln‚Äôs Gettysburg address, ‚ÄúThis Nation Under God,‚Äù as well as Psalm 16:1. These symbols reflect the faith that has guided our nation through every chapter of its history.

As a Catholic, I pray daily to guide my decisions, shape my values, and ground my work on behalf of the people I serve. I‚Äôm deeply grateful for this spiritual refuge in the Capitol, where faith meets duty.

May God bless our families.
May God bless our communities.
And may God bless the United States of America.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: What‚Äôs at stake for public broadcasting if the Senate‚Äôs rescissions package passes in the House üßµ

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 1/ The rescissions package guts funding for public broadcasting which is the backbone of quality educational content and trusted news for millions of Americans. Over 1,500 stations serve the country including 250 in rural areas where they are often the only source of reliable information.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 3/ PBS children‚Äôs programming like Daniel Tiger‚Äôs Neighborhood, Sesame Street, Super Why, and Peg + Cat have decades of rigorous research proving their positive impact on early childhood development.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 2/ Public broadcasting is not just TV or radio. It is a lifeline. During extreme weather events and emergencies, public broadcasters provide critical safety information that can save lives. Cutting this funding puts public safety at serious risk.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 4/ A UCLA study found nearly 75% of teens who watched Daniel Tiger remember its social-emotional lessons years later‚Äîskills like managing emotions and problem solving that shape healthy adults.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 5/ Sesame Street viewers perform better on standardized tests for literacy, math, and vocabulary. It fosters pro-social behaviors like sharing and cooperation, helping kids succeed academically and socially.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 6/ These programs are especially crucial for low-income families and rural communities who rely heavily on public broadcasting for educational resources that are not accessible elsewhere.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 7/ Globally, Sesame Street has helped children in more than 15 countries learn literacy, numeracy, science, health, and safety, demonstrating the broad proven impact of public broadcasting beyond our borders.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 8/ Cutting $1 billion from public broadcasting funding is not just an attack on education‚Äîit is an attack on equity, public safety, and the right to reliable information.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text: 9/ As the House prepares to vote, know this: slashing funds for public broadcasting will hurt kids, endanger lives during emergencies, and silence reliable voices in rural America.

This has been a long time coming: I've been working with Annie Harris and the other dedicated leaders of the Essex Heritage Area and Salem Maritime Site since 2021, building off of years of great partnership since I first came to Congress.

Becoming a National Historical Park means that Salem Maritime will have access to the resources it deserves‚Äîmeaning more locals and visitors alike can enjoy all that Salem has to offer. 

It's no easy feat to pass a bill into law, especially in the minority, but it's a testament to the advocacy and determination. Thank you to Senator Markey for his partnership over in the Senate.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
Crypto is here to stay. That‚Äôs why we can‚Äôt afford to wait any longer to establish guardrails that protect consumers and bring long-overdue transparency to this rapidly evolving industry.
¬†
I voted YES on the GENIUS Act because it‚Äôs a meaningful step toward ensuring that Americans who choose to invest in stablecoins are protected from fraud and abuse. This bill is far from perfect and more must be done to confront the blatant corruption we‚Äôre seeing from Donald Trump, who has shamelessly used his position as President to line his pockets with millions in crypto. I‚Äôll keep fighting for strong anti-corruption legislation to stop the kind of self-dealing that‚Äôs happening in plain sight.
¬†
I voted NO on the CLARITY Act. I support a regulatory framework that distinguishes between digital assets, fosters innovation, and promotes responsible growth, but this bill simply doesn‚Äôt get us there. It‚Äôs riddled with loopholes and carveouts that leave everyday investors exposed to the kinds of volatile, often fraudulent crypto schemes we‚Äôve seen too regularly with memecoins. It fails to strike the right balance between innovation and consumer protection. As the bill moves to the Senate, it‚Äôs critical that our colleagues strengthen it, starting with ensuring that states like Massachusetts retain the authority to crack down on fraud and abuse.
¬†
I believe we can support innovation in the crypto space while standing firmly against the predatory practices that have taken root in the absence of meaningful oversight. The future of digital assets should be built on transparency, accountability, and protections for everyday investors. That‚Äôs the balance I‚Äôll keep fighting for.

text:
My meeting with Secretary of the Army Daniel Driscoll focused on the Army Transformation Initiative (ATI) and the vital, strategic role Texas plays in advancing the Army‚Äôs modernization goals.

Given the Army presence at the Corpus Christi and Red River Army Depots, Army Futures Command, Forts Hood and Bliss, Joint Base San Antonio and other critical military installations, it‚Äôs clear that Texas offers unmatched advantages in infrastructure, workforce, and geographic positioning. Texas is the most capable and ready state to accelerate Army transformation.

The conversation reinforced that Texas has long served as the backbone of American defense‚Äîhome to hundreds of thousands of servicemembers, military families, and a robust defense industrial base. With world-class installations and proven readiness, Texas is uniquely positioned to lead the next era of the U.S. Army.

I affirmed that Texas should not just be a participant, but a core partner in what ATI represents: forward-leaning innovation, operational agility, and strategic readiness. The discussion highlighted the critical importance of protecting and expanding the missions at Red River Army Depot (RRAD), Joint Base San Antonio (JBSA), and Army Futures Command (AFC)‚Äîeach of which plays an indispensable role in supporting the Army‚Äôs current and future force.

The meeting also included proposals to relocate additional Army missions and capabilities to Texas. These actions would strengthen ATI implementation while maximizing efficiency, speed, and national security outcomes.

This meeting reflects Texas‚Äôs continued leadership and commitment to ensuring the U.S. Army remains the most capable, modern, and ready force in the world - with Texas at its core.

Name: Brecheen, Josh
text:
Today I voted to advance the CBDC Anti-Surveillance State Act out of the House, in tandem with the GENIUS Act and the Clarity Act, which will ensure that there will never be a central bank digital currency created. The bills passed today will allow a cohesive and commonsense framework in which stablecoins (digital assets that are pegged to actual assets such as the USD) can be bought, sold, and traded similar to stocks, without being designated as securities. One important note, these stablecoins are not government run, created, or controlled‚Äìthey are part of the free market and thus their use is not required.¬†

The passage of these three bills is yet another step forward in bringing forth the golden era that President Trump has promised and will provide regulatory clarity in the markets.¬†

Now that the House has passed the CBDC Anti-Surveillance State Act, it is the Senate‚Äôs responsibility to take it up and pass it. In the event that the Senate does not take it up, House Freedom Caucus, in coordination with White House and Leadership, was able to secure a commitment that anti-central bank digital currency language will be included in the National Defense Authorization Act, a ‚Äòmust pass‚Äô bill that is advanced annually.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
During today‚Äôs Appropriations markup, the committee adopted my amendment to the FY26 Transportation, Housing and Urban Development bill to prohibit civilian drones from airspace within one mile of the southern border.

Cartels are using drones to track Border Patrol and troop movements, enabling the smuggling of drugs, weapons, and people into the U.S. These systems are growing more advanced and harder to detect, putting border communities and law enforcement at serious risk. Unlike responsible operators, cartels don‚Äôt follow regulations ‚Äî they adapt quickly to evade detection. This amendment helps our agents match that agility by giving them the tools and authority to respond in real time.

Working with @RepCloudTX, we developed bipartisan language that directs @FAANews, @DHSgov, and @CBP to create a no-drone zone along the southern border. It targets illegal activity without disrupting responsible drone use. The amendment also includes clear exceptions for law enforcement, emergency responders, and legal operators like farmers and ranchers.

This sends a clear message: Congress recognizes the threat and expects federal agencies to act swiftly to counter it.

I remain committed to securing the border, protecting our communities, and ensuring law enforcement has what it needs to get the job done. I thank Chairman @rep_stevewomack and Ranking Member @RepJamesClyburn for supporting this commonsense, bipartisan step to safeguard our homeland.

During today‚Äôs Appropriations markup, I was pleased to help secure two provisions in the FY26 Energy and Water bill: one to improve flash flood preparedness, and another to support rehabilitation of the Amistad and Falcon Dams.

This summer‚Äôs flash flooding in Central Texas was devastating. I‚Äôm deeply familiar with the region ‚Äì I live nearby, and my kids have attended summer camp around that area. I visited the flood-affected communities and spoke directly with first responders. I helped secure a provision that will ensure the @USACEHQ, in coordination with @NOAA, @USGS, and @fema, prioritize technical assistance for local communities and improve flood response planning using the best available science and data.

Public broadcasting isn‚Äôt just Big Bird and Sesame Street ‚Äì it‚Äôs how families in Massachusetts and across the country get lifesaving emergency alerts, stay connected to their communities, and access trusted, educational programming. Slashing support for public radio and television will silence local newsrooms, especially in rural areas, and undermine the emergency broadcast systems we rely on in times of crisis.

We saw the consequences of weakened alert systems during the catastrophic floods in Texas. Communities were caught flat-footed, in part because they lacked access to timely, reliable emergency broadcasts. Contrast that with what we saw just yesterday in Alaska, where public broadcasters immediately issued alerts after a powerful 7.3 magnitude offshore earthquake, potentially saving lives. These two realities show exactly what‚Äôs at stake. If these cuts move forward, the Trump administration will be making a conscious choice to leave communities more vulnerable, more isolated, and less safe.

I voted no because I will always stand up for public safety, for local journalism, and for the families who depend on these vital services every single day.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
This week Congress passed crypto legislation.

The American people hardly have any idea what it is, what it means, and what passed.

1. GENUIS ACT - I voted NO. It passed the Senate and the House and will be signed into law today. 
This bill regulates stablecoins and provides for the backdoor Centralized Bank Digital Currency. The Federal Reserve has been planning a CBDC for years and this will open the door to move you to a cashless society and into digital currency that can be weaponized against you by an authoritarian government controlling your ability to buy and sell. Do you actually trust your government to never do that to you? I don‚Äôt.

2. Anti-CBDC Surveillance State Act - I voted YES. This bill passed the House but we were told all week that it will not pass the Senate because the Senate does not have any path at all to get 60 votes to ban a CBDC. This bill prohibits Federal Reserve Banks from issuing a Central Bank Digital Currency. It‚Äôs a good bill and protects your money, but will die in the Senate. However, this should be people‚Äôs highest demand.

3. Clarity Act - I voted YES for self custody protections. This bill passed the House and will likely get some changes in the Senate then have come back to the House for another vote before it can be signed by the President and become law. This bill establishes a detailed regulatory framework for digital assets and allocates authority between the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) and the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). The most important thing that needs to remain is protecting people‚Äôs self custody of their digital currency. This is yet to be seen and should be demanded. I will vote NO when it comes back if self custody protections are taken out.

In 1971, we were taken off the gold standard to cash, which was a ridiculous decision and has weakened our dollar tremendously.

Now we are on the path to move from cash you can hold in your hand, hide from the government, and save for yourself and your family to a digital currency system where your ability to buy and sell will ultimately be held in digital accounts that you can not tangibly hold yet are at the will of those who control the banks and the government.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
94% of the amendments I introduced in @HASCRepublicans are now part of the NDAA.

Every one was written in my office, fought for in committee, and built to strengthen our national defense.

For our troops. For their mission. For our country.

Here‚Äôs what made it in ‚¨áÔ∏èüßµ

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
1. Banning adversary-owned businesses from U.S. military bases.

Companies tied to China, Russia, Iran, or North Korea shouldn‚Äôt be running shops for American servicemembers.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
2. Closing a loophole for Chinese government-backed firms operating abroad.

If a company answers to Beijing, it shouldn‚Äôt be doing business with the Pentagon, no matter where it‚Äôs headquartered.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
3. Phasing out Chinese pharmaceutical ingredients from the military supply chain.

We shouldn‚Äôt depend on the CCP for medicines used to treat American troops.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
4. Powering military data centers with on-base nuclear energy.

Small modular reactors give our most sensitive systems 24/7 protection from grid failure or attack.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
6. Advancing stealth drones that can survive in high-threat zones.

New designs focus on low visibility, acoustic reduction, and survivability in contested airspace.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
5. Rebuilding America‚Äôs drone supply chain.

Too much of our unmanned aircraft technology is built overseas, this starts bringing that production home.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
7. Using AI to speed up military construction.

Base projects are stuck in bureaucratic bottlenecks, AI helps streamline planning and approvals.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
8. Standardizing battlefield battery systems with U.S.-made tech.

The current system is fragmented and foreign-sourced, this shifts us to reliable, modular, American-made power.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
10. Testing smart fire controls on next-gen infantry rifles.

Before we field new weapon systems, we need to be sure they work under real combat conditions.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
9. Expanding access to anonymous mental health care for troops.

Servicemembers deserve private, stigma-free ways to get support when they need it.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
11. Funding development of long-range glide munitions.

These precision weapons are critical to keeping up with China, Russia, and modern threats.

Proud to share that two of my key defense funding priorities were included in the FY26 Defense Appropriations bill, without increasing overall spending. This is a strategic shift in how existing funds are prioritized to better protect our national security.

SMART Hub research at @Baylor University will receive funding to advance cutting-edge RF and radar technologies. These innovations will enhance spectrum dominance on the battlefield and improve safety for our service members.

Additionally, funding was reallocated for a Department of Defense initiative to improve microelectronics security. This investment will fund a proof-of-concept for embedding unalterable security markings directly onto chips, marking a critical step toward full-spectrum semiconductor assurance across both our defense and critical infrastructure.

This bill demonstrates that we can make smart, future-focused investments in national defense by focusing resources where they‚Äôre needed most.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we recognize a Hometown Hero‚Äîsomeone whose impact on our community is lasting, profound, and deeply felt.
 
This week, we honor someone who has long embodied that title: Carla Reynolds. While she was named a Hometown Hero before, it only felt right‚Äîespecially this week‚Äîto honor her once more.
 
This past weekend, we gathered for Unity Day, the event Carla built with love, vision, and purpose. It was moving, powerful, and unmistakably her. Though her physical presence was missing, her spirit filled every corner of that celebration.
 
Carla believed in the power of unity, not as a slogan, but as a way of life. Through Unity Day and her Boots on the Ground Foundation, she brought people together across every divide, fed families in crisis, and gave hope to those who felt unseen or unheard. She believed in meeting people where they are‚Äîand lifting them up with dignity and grace.
 
She also poured her heart into our young people, spotlighting Bucks County students who excelled in school, in service, and in sports‚Äîbecause, in her words, ‚ÄúOur kids need to know we see them.‚Äù
 
Carla made our community feel more whole, more connected, more compassionate, more human. Her life was a living example of what it means to love your neighbor. And though we said goodbye far too soon, we will continue to celebrate her, carry forward her mission, and ensure that Unity Day remains a tradition that reflects her values and vision.
 
To her daughter Tamara and all who loved her: thank you for sharing Carla with us‚Äîshe will forever be our Hometown Hero.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today, I held a press conference alongside Mayor Trevi√±o to update the community on how the Department of Defense is supporting border security here in Laredo.
¬†
Last week, I toured one of the Stryker units with Mayor Trevi√±o, Customs and Border Protection, and Army leadership to see firsthand how these armored vehicles equipped with thermal imaging and drone detection technology are helping strengthen our border security. These assets provide critical surveillance in the dense brush where illegal crossings often happen, giving Border Patrol real-time intelligence and allowing agents to respond more effectively and safely.
¬†
I also spoke with Major General Scott Naumann, Commander of Joint Task Force‚ÄìSouthwest Border, to hear directly what our troops need to succeed. The challenges we face are real and growing. Earlier this week, I was briefed on an alarming incident where an Army official was assaulted by an undocumented individual hiding in thick brush. Thankfully no one was injured, but these kinds of threats are increasing. Laredo now ranks among the top cities for cartel-operated drone activity, and the Rio Grande brush accounts for the vast majority of illegal crossings and concealment.
¬†
The Stryker units are already making an impact. Their cameras can detect movement as small as a mouse from over a mile away, helping Border Patrol focus resources where they are needed and deterring illegal crossings. Clearing overgrown vegetation is also critical to improving visibility and patrol mobility. The Stryker units are prepared to assist with clearing key zones in coordination with the International Boundary and Water Commission and local groups to ensure it‚Äôs done responsibly and transparently.
¬†
These vehicles remain on perimeter routes and use sensors, not weapons, to scan from a distance. They are not patrolling our streets or enforcing immigration law. This is a precision mission focused on deterring cartel drones, disrupting smuggling networks, and ensuring the safety of our frontline officers.
¬†
In Congress, I am working to fund river-road improvements, expand patrol access routes, remove Carrizo cane, and modernize federal law so Border Patrol and military units have the tools and protections they need.
¬†
I want to thank Mayor Trevi√±o, Chief Mu√±oz, @DHSgov , @DeptofDefense , and our local law enforcement for working in lockstep to¬†reducing cartel-drone incursions, illegal crossings, stash houses, and high-speed car chases. This unified effort across all levels of government is delivering results.
¬†
South Texas is strong and resilient. When we work together and lead with facts, not fear, we rise to any challenge. To every soldier, agent, and neighbor, thank you. I will keep fighting for you in Washington and listening to you here at home.

Name: Panetta, Jimmy
text:
I grew up in our Congressional District and have seen firsthand the growing issues with affordability that affect those of us who actually live here. That‚Äôs why affordable housing is my number one issue as the proud U.S. Representative for our home.  It‚Äôs why I introduced a legislative package as a member of the House Ways and Means Committee to help tackle this crisis from every angle: expanding tax credits to build more workforce housing, helping first-time homebuyers afford a down payment, freeing up existing housing stock, and co-leading the Rent Relief Act to put money back in renters' pockets when housing costs soar.

CA-19 was named the least affordable rental market in the U.S. To afford a modest two-bedroom, you‚Äôd need to earn $81.21/hour. That‚Äôs five full-time jobs at minimum wage. 

As your Federal Representative, I continue to fight the challenges that we face when it comes to affordability. I don‚Äôt just talk about it, I‚Äôm actually doing something about it to ensure that the federal government plays its part to ensure that living in CA-19 is more affordable.

text: üßµLast month, 325 Mayors, Tribal, and First Nation leaders committed to clean water, US-Canada relations, and climate resilience. Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: Here are just some of the declarations and resolutions passed this year at the Great Lakes and St. Lawrence Cities Initiative Annual Meeting:

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution¬†entitled ‚ÄúAdvancing a Great Lakes-St. Lawrence Strong Response to the US-Canada Trade War,‚Äù highlighting the Cities Initiative‚Äôs strong opposition to blanket US tariffs on Canadian goods.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A declaration entitled ‚ÄúPreserving the US-Canada Relationship to Protect Our Prosperous Regional Economy and Our Precious Freshwater Resources,‚Äù that commits the Cities Initiative to working tirelessly to improve ties between the United States and Canada.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution entitled ‚ÄúUpholding the Great Lakes-St. Lawrence River Basin Agreement and Compact,‚Äù reaffirming the Cities Initiative‚Äôs unwavering support for the Agreement and Compact ‚Äì especially the ban on out-of-basin diversions.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution¬†entitled, "Reaffirming Support for the Great Lakes Water Quality Agreement,"¬†to express the Cities Initiative's ongoing support for the GLWQA and other transboundary efforts to maintain and improve water quality.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution¬†entitled ‚ÄúProtecting US Federal Funding to Combat Erosion and Flooding Across the Great Lakes and St. Lawrence River Basin,‚Äù calling on Congress to reject proposed funding cuts to NOAA programs that strengthen coastal resilience.

Name: Kaptur, Marcy
text: A resolution entitled ‚ÄúMaintaining Progress on Lead Service Line Replacement Through the Lead and Copper Rule Improvements,‚Äù encouraging Congress to reject any effort to repeal or weaken the Lead and Copper Rule Improvements.

U.S. Border Patrol agents face a growing challenge as cartels use civilian drones to surveil and evade law enforcement along the southern border. These off-the-shelf drones give criminal groups the ability to coordinate smuggling operations faster than ever before, threatening community safety and border security.

To address this head-on, I secured a bipartisan amendment with @RepCloudTX in the FY26 Transportation, Housing and Urban Development directing federal agencies to establish a no-drone zone within one mile of the border. This measure empowers agents to respond swiftly and maintain their tactical advantage, ensuring they can operate with speed and adjust to evolving threats.

Protecting our border means staying ahead of those who seek to exploit technology to undermine security. This amendment is a crucial step in giving our agents the tools and authority they need to keep our communities safe.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: There are two rings in this circus.¬†Most of the focus has been on Ring One: the badly abused Senate confirmation process, and our walkout as the majority broke committee rules to get Trump‚Äôs thug cleared through committee without answering questions.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text:
The race is on.

Republicans are moving today to Emil Bove‚Äôs nomination, rushing to get Trump‚Äôs thug cleared through the Senate while two Trump judges hold up the court contempt hearing that would bring out the facts hidden from us in Judiciary.

üßµ

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Not only did the majority let Bove dodge answering questions in Ring One, they gave pre-clearance with hand-waving about executive privileges Congress had never conceded apply against Congress‚Äôs powers of inquiry ‚Äî greenlight to stonewall.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: With that signal, Bove never even properly asserted privileges. That would have met legal consternation about wrongful assertion. Having got the signal, he just refused, as ‚Äúinappropriate,‚Äù or ‚Äúnot public‚Äù or ‚Äúdon‚Äôt recall.‚Äù That‚Äôs not how privilege works.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Our questions focused on three instances of prosecutorial misconduct. In one, the ‚Äúf*** you‚Äù instance, there was a well-corroborated whistleblower. That was also the instance where a judge had found probable cause for a contempt hearing.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Then they broke the committee rules to ram the Trump thug through. When there‚Äôs an objection to a vote, the rules require a committee vote on moving to the vote. The chair just called the Bove vote, and the roll was called, even over a senator still speaking.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: That was the nasty business being performed in Ring One.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: They say that had been done before. No. Not like this. Only when Republicans used another rule to cancel a committee meeting, so we had to move to the vote; or when there had already been full debate in a previous meeting. This was a new low.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Meanwhile, Ring Two is over at the Circuit Court of Appeals, where Trump judges Rao and Katsas, over objection, stopped the court hearing into Bove‚Äôs potential contempt in the deportation cases. In court, under oath, answers would be hard to dodge.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The administrative stay procedure the Trump judges used usually only lasts days. Justice Barrett recently suggested a two-week administrative stay would be too long. This one has lasted three months, blocking the hearing that would have brought Bove‚Äôs misconduct to light.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: It‚Äôs hard to imagine that this isn‚Äôt a coordinated play, where one hand of the Trump operation gets an evidentiary hearing into a nominee‚Äôs misconduct blocked while another hand of the Trump operation gets the nominee rammed through confirmation.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: This stinks to high heaven.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Here's a hard but necessary truth:

For decades, our civil rights laws have been used not to prevent discrimination, but to enforce it.

Rather than protecting the equal rights of all citizens, the civil rights bureaucracy has become the enforcement arm of a new caste system.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Tomorrow, I'm leading a hearing on how we can forcibly dismantle the DEI regime.

For too long, our civil rights bureaucracy has aided and abetted discrimination.

It's time for lawbreakers to pay the price.

I'll be calling @HarmeetKDhillon and @GeneHamiltonUSA to testify. üßµ

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
This new system has gone by many names.

Today, it has found its most radical and extreme expression in the form of "diversity, equity, and inclusion" ‚Äî or DEI.

DEI is not just illegal ‚Äî it's a fraudulent and cynical doctrine, from top to bottom, built upon layers of lies.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
And finally, it's not about "inclusion." It's about exclusion‚Äîof the competent, the qualified, the meritorious‚Äîwhen those people are members of the "wrong" race or sex.

Over the past few decades, this poisonous and brazenly illegal doctrine has transformed our institutions.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
It's not about "diversity." It's about discrimination‚Äîa sustained campaign of collective punishment, wrapped in the rhetoric of social justice.

It's not about "equity." It's about power. They don't want to "level the playing field"‚Äîthey want to elevate some groups over others.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: In many blue states, DEI is now entrenched in every level of government decision-making. At the federal level, it's produced a vast universe of civil service preferences, billions of dollars in taxpayer-funded minority-only grants, and open racial discrimination in contracting.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: In the universities, DEI has meant the abolition of merit. Even after the Supreme Court banned race-based admissions in 2023, elite schools like Harvard and Stanford just rebranded their quotas, embedding them in essay prompts and hiring policies rather than ending them outright.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
In the corporate world, DEI has meant hiring and promotion not on the basis of competence, but on the basis of race and sex‚Äîa world where one‚Äôs place in the new caste system determines who rises and who falls.
https://t.co/K3TvFtltEg

text:

No racial preferences. No double standards. No legal fictions like "disparate impact."

Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
The crimes of Jeffrey Epstein and his enablers shattered countless lives and exposed a vast system of exploitation and violence against women and girls.

Today, I am proud to join as a cosponsor of the Epstein Files Transparency Act ‚Äî a vital step toward truth and accountability in the face of unspeakable abuse. With this resolution, we declare unequivocally that violence against women will not be ignored.  

For years, Epstein‚Äôs victims ‚Äî many of them just children when they were abused ‚Äî have waited for justice, often in silence and in pain. 

They deserve answers. They deserve dignity. And they deserve action from their government. 

That is why it is especially shameful that Speaker Johnson has shut down the House of Representatives for the summer to avoid a vote on this resolution. 

To block transparency in this manner is not only an abdication of duty ‚Äî it is a profound insult to the victims who have carried the burden of this trauma for decades.  

The American people deserve to know the full extent of who was involved with Epstein and all of them must be held accountable ‚Äî no matter how powerful. 

As we pursue accountability, we must respect the voices and privacy of the survivors to honor their courage, protect their dignity, and ensure that the full truth comes to light. 

Justice delayed is justice denied. The American people ‚Äî and the survivors ‚Äî deserve better.

Name: Sullivan, Dan
text:
The PRO Vets Act has passed the House! My legislation passed the Senate earlier this month and will now go to the President to be signed into law. 

I introduced this legislation after a shocking budget debacle at the VA under the Biden administration: a supposed multi-billion-dollar budget shortfall in mid-2024 followed by a multi-billion-dollar surplus two months later. The PRO Vets Act works to re-establish accountability at the VA by mandating quarterly, in-person budget reports to Congress and withholding bonuses for senior VA and Office of Management and Budget (OMB) personnel if there are future financial shortfalls.

As a member of @SVACGOP, I will continue working closely with @secvetaffairs Doug Collins who supports greater accountability, to hold the VA to the high standards the American people expect and to ensure our veterans are receiving the care and benefits they have earned.
